;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399260" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1663340399260"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">✅ Wrist Support</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399261" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663340399261" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>The very first benefit that wrist wraps give is joint support. Most athletes use them for this reason and all other points on my list stem from this one, too.&nbsp;</p><p>It comes in especially handy if you have thin wrists that need an additional boost to deal with heavy weights. Most athletes can add a few kilograms to their training loads when they start using wraps. It is the result of improved stability, mechanics, coordination, and confidence as well.</p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702279327543" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702279327543" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="font-weight: bold;"><span style="color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">Our expert,</span>&nbsp;<a href="https://torokhtiy.com/pages/sergii-putsov" class="" target="_blank">Sergiy Putsov</a><span style="color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">, noted:</span></span></p><p><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">“In my lifting sessions, I've found wrist wraps most useful when performing heavy presses, jerks, or snatches, as they provide the necessary wrist support and stability, helping prevent strain or injury. For me, the most important characteristics are that the material does not "cut" the skin of the forearm, has a comfortable fixation and wash normally.”</span></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399264" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1663340399264"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">✅ Injury Prevention</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399263" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663340399263" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>As wrist wraps support and keep your joints fixed, they also reduce the risk of injury. When you constantly work with extreme weights, this benefit may give you the courage to hit a new PR and, most importantly, do that safely.</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399274" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1663340399274" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/dda265ef-9e61-4e3d-af8b-e006bb6b5c80/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/wrist-wraps-torokhtiy.jpg" alt="Wrist wraps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="1000px" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399265" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1663340399265"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">✅ Pain Relief</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399266" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663340399266" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>As wraps take most of the load away from the wrists, they may relieve joint pain pretty well. If you have had any injuries in the past or just feel any discomfort while lifting weights, try out wrist wraps to soothe the pain.</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1665694150992" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1665694150992"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">✅ Improved Technique</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1665694157007" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1665694157007" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Additional support and stability in the wrists give you a better sense of the space and moves. In this way, you may notice a significant improvement in the technique and mechanics. This benefit is also tightly connected with safety as well as higher performance.</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702367005022" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1702367005022" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/d0ed51ed-19c1-4a5f-83f9-2b13fade0832/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/What%20Are%20the%20Benefits%20of%20Using%20Wrist%20Wraps%20for%20Lifting%20_1_.png" alt="benefits of using wrist wraps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="benefits of using wrist wraps" width="1200" height="800" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399268" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1663340399268"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">What Are Possible Disadvantages of Wrist Wraps?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663340399267" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663340399267"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">As great as they are, wrist wraps can sometimes do more harm than good. If you rely on them too much, it could weaken your wrist muscles and hinder your natural strength development over time. Remember that they’re meant to be used as a tool, not as a crutch.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">They can also limit your wrists’ mobility during lifting, because continuous use can hinder your joints’ “functional” range of motion, which can affect your performance in exercises that rely on the flexibility of  your wrists under load. Your grip strength can also suffer, because if your muscles are constantly receiving external support, they won’t have the need to strengthen naturally.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Skin irritation is rather common as well due to the friction between your skin and the wraps. This can also happen if your wraps don’t fit properly.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702279134226" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702279134226"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"><strong><span style="color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">Our expert,</span>&nbsp;<a href="https://torokhtiy.com/pages/tanya-shaiko" class="" target="_blank">Jacek</a>&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">added:</span></strong></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"><strong><i>“I use wrist wraps only in the case of higher volume work like my dynamic effort day when the wrist is exposed to the high repetitions and its strength/endurance is becoming a limiting factor in my performance. Not really using it outside of that situation to avoid over-reliance. Ones I’m using - WBCM - why? Because there is literally nothing I’d change in them - they are like custom made for me 🙂”</i></strong></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027200670" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027200670"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">When Do You Need Wrist Support?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027204646" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027204646"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Wrist wraps are mainly used for wrist support and stability. You may need it to perform extreme lifts that put pressure on your joints: the bench press, overhead press, jerk, snatch, squats, etc. Generally, you can put them on whenever you feel any discomfort.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Wrist wraps bring the most benefit for powerlifting but also come in handy in Olympic weightlifting, bodybuilding, functional training and fitness. They improve technique and mechanics and that’s why some athletes can add a few kilograms to the bar once they wrap their wrists. Thus, using them to hit your dream PR also makes sense.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702279458470" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702279458470"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><span style="color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">Our expert,</span>&nbsp;<a href="https://torokhtiy.com/pages/tanya-shaiko" class="" target="_blank">Tanya Shaiko</a><span style="color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">, shared her experience:</span></span></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">“I use them really often, when my wrists hurt. They are helpful for wrist support during heavy overhead lifts, overhead squats, jerks, front squats. I recommend using them, especially when you feel discomfort or weakness in your wrists during workouts with barbells, kettlebells, dumbbells, handstands, etc. It is important to be comfortable for long workouts.”</span></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702279447402" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702279447402"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Additionally, athletes may want some compression to relieve wrist pain. If you have had any joint injuries in the past, fixing your wrists in place usually gives you a sense of safety and comfort. So if weight training is still on your dream list because of any joint issues, give wrist wraps a chance.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-3 gf_col-md-3 gf_col-sm-3 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1656408980788" data-id="1656408980788"></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1663341660741" class="gf_row gf_row-fluid gf_row-no-padding gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1663341660741" data-extraclass="" data-row-gap="0px" style="display: block;"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1655318047095" data-id="1655318047095"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1663341660700" class="gf_row" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1663341660700" data-layout-lg="9+3" data-extraclass="" data-layout-md="9+3" data-layout-sm="9+3" data-layout-xs="12+12" style="display: block;"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-9 gf_col-md-9 gf_col-sm-9 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1656408976790" data-id="1656408976790"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1663341660727" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1663341660727" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass=""><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1658814063462" data-id="1658814063462"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1663341660766" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1663341660766" style="min-height: auto;" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass=""><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1656316047890" data-id="1656316047890" style="min-height: 1px; display: block; flex-direction: unset; justify-content: unset;"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1663341660755" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1663341660755" data-layout-lg="12" data-extraclass="" data-layout-md="12" data-layout-sm="12" data-layout-xs="12" style="display: block;" data-row-gap="0px"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1656408976790" data-id="1656408976790"><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660645" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1663341660645"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">What to Look for in Lifting Wrist Wraps?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660711" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663341660711"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">While looking for wrist support for lifting, pay attention to some key features that can make a significant difference.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660798" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1663341660798"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">1. Size</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660681" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663341660681" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>As for the size, wrist wraps usually differ in length. The bottom line is that the longer a wrap is, the more stability it gives. Thus, if you seek the highest compression and support, you may need a long option – it will provide more solid coverage. Also, if you have huge forearms and wrists, you may find a big size very handy.</p><p>On the other hand, if you are a female with tiny wrists, you may need a shorter option. It will be easier to put on and will give a more comfortable fit. Also, such wraps are better for dynamic exercises that need mobility and versatility.</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027276807" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1702027276807"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">2. Adjustability</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027278808" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027278808" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>This is a very important feature because wraps that can’t be adjusted to fit properly won’t do what they’re supposed to do. Look for wraps that offer flexibility in sizing to suit different hand and wrist dimensions, and also look at the method of adjustment. Velcro straps are great at reinforcing stability and allowing you to tailor the tension, but make sure the Velcro quality is good. Thumb loops are another great feature because they ensure proper positioning.</p><p>There are, of course, other closure types, like the hook-and-loop twist and tuck and elastic closures. Each of these offer varying degrees of adjustability and allow you to customize the wraps to your comfort and support needs.</p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702030940931" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1702030940931" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/d04b04f6-d0f8-47b3-8695-2211dbf93df7/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/woman-using-wrist-wraps.jpg" alt="Getting ready for the training with wrist wraps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="Getting ready for the training with wrist wraps" width="1200" height="800" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660754" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1663341660754"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">3. Material</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660723" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663341660723" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Material is all about comfort and support. In a nutshell, if wraps are made mainly of cotton, they will be sturdier and more rigid. It means less stretch and higher stability and support. On the other hand, such options may be slightly harsh on the skin but that is not a problem if you know the price for the highest fixation.</p><p>Still, most options are made of elastic, nylon, and polyester blends. Such wraps are softer and easier to put on. They also give you more versatility and flexibility rather than strong support.</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660744" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1663341660744"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">4. Certification</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660682" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663341660682" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Wrist wraps are allowed at powerlifting meets but still have some rules to keep in mind. The most important point is that the length should be below 1 m and the width should not exceed 8 cm.&nbsp;</p><p>Other regulations are about the use of wrist wraps. You shouldn’t go more than 10 cm from the center to the forearm and 2 cm to the hand. Thus, the overall coverage should be within 12 cm. Also, don’t forget to take the loop off the thumb before a set.</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027335827" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1702027335827"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">5. Stiffness</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027339128" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027339128" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>You want wraps that are rigid enough to offer support but do not restrict natural movement. Ideal wrist wraps have a level of firmness that stabilizes your wrists during, for example, heavy lifting, which helps prevent injuries.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027371504" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1702027371504"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">6. Closure Type</span></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027376166" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027376166" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Closure mechanism is a big deal because that is what secures the wrap to your wrists and makes the fit precise. Hook-and-loop closures (also known as Velcro) are very easy to adjust and allow you to customize the tension and tightness so that the fit can be snug but still comfortable. Some wraps have elastic elements that improve the wraps’ security and prevent them from slipping and shifting during your workouts.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702402575819" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1702402575819" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/065ca630-2f0f-4155-beb5-31bd1c0bbe41/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/What%20to%20Look%20for%20in%20Lifting%20Wrist%20Wraps%20_1_.png" alt="What to look for in wrist wraps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="What to look for in wrist wraps" width="1200" height="800" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660655" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1663341660655"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">How to Use Wrist Wraps for Lifting?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660632" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1663341660632"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">First, put your thumb in a loop to keep a wrap in place while <a href="https://powerliftingtechnique.com/how-to-use-wrist-wraps/" class="" target="_blank">putting it on</a>. Then, wrap it around your wrist with desirable compression and fasten the tail on the velcro. You can cover any area that you want and vary the tension. Now, you can take the loop off the thumb.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1663341660668" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1663341660668" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/ec99a926-25a0-4db5-bc13-3d078d1cbf3a/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/push-ups-using-wrist-wraps-torokhtiy.jpg" alt="Training with wrist wraps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="1000px" data-height="auto" title="Training with wrist wraps" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702279547398" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702279547398"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">If you are using our winner – the WBCM wrist wraps – tuck a tail under the string to fix everything in place.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702279581077" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702279581077"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><a href="https://torokhtiy.com/pages/oleksiy-torokhtiy" class="" target="_blank">Oleksiy Torokhtiy</a>&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">gave us some tips of using wrist wraps:</span></span></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"><span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">“I recommend using wrist wraps after warming up. Ideal use, after 50-70% of your best result. This will allow you to use small muscles that very often do not work when we start using wrist wraps. So, I don’t recommend training with them all the time.”</span></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027445175" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027445175"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Wrist Wraps vs Wrist Straps vs Gloves - Choosing the Right Gear for Our Lifting Needs</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027448094" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027448094"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Wrist wraps are great and a lot of people can’t imagine their workout routine without them, but that doesn’t mean they’re going to be perfect for you. There are other options when it comes to wrist support and knowing the differences between them can help you make a better choice.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Wrist wraps are designed primarily to stabilize and support the wrist joint. They provide compression and may reduce the risk of injuries during pressing exercises (like weightlifting, powerlifting, etc.). They reinforce your wrists, limit excessive movement, and act like an extra layer of protection for your ligaments and tendons. They’re popular with people who want support for their wrists.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702027493723" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1702027493723"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Wrist straps on the other hand, are focused more on lowering the strength demands  of your grip during lifting rather than focusing specifically on your wrists. They’re used during heavy lifts to reduce the grip strength demands and allow you to concentrate on engaging your target muscle groups without worrying about your grip failing. They wrap around the wrist, and then around a barbell or dumbbell.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;">Gloves have a dual purpose: they protect your palms against calluses, blisters, and abrasions and provide an additional layer for better grip (especially when dealing with slippery or sweaty equipment). They’re popular among people who want to protect their hands and wrists while maintaining a secure grip, especially when it comes to exercises like pull-ups, rope climbs, or anything involving kettlebells.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit !important;"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit